{"title_page": "Sangtuda 1 Hydroelectric Power Plant", "text_new": "{{Infobox dam\n| name                 = Sangtuda 1 Hydroelectric Power Plant\n| name_official        = Sangtudinskaya GES-1\n| image                = Sangtuda 1.jpg\n| image_size           = \n| image_caption        = Sangtuda 1 Hydroelectric Power Plant\n| image_alt            = \n| location_map         = Tajikistan\n| location_map_size    = \n| location_map_caption = Location of the Sangtuda 1 Hydroelectric Power Plant within Tajikistan\n| coordinates          = {{coord|38|02|42|N|69|03|30|E|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| country              = [[Tajikistan]]\n| location             = [[Danghara District]], [[Khatlon Province]]\n| status               = O\n| construction_began   = 1989\n| opening              = 2009\n| demolished           = \n| cost                 = US$720&nbsp;million\n| owner                = [[Government of Russia]] (66.39%)<br>[[Government of Tajikistan]] (16.45%)<br>[[FGC UES]] (14.92%)<br>[[Inter RAO UES]] (2.24%)\n| dam_type             = \n| dam_height           = {{convert|75|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| dam_height_thalweg   =\n| dam_height_foundation=\n| dam_length           = {{convert|517|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| dam_width_crest      = \n| dam_width_base       = \n| dam_volume           = \n| dam_elevation_crest  =\n| dam_crosses          = [[Vakhsh River]]\n| spillway_count       = \n| spillway_type        = \n| spillway_capacity    = \n| res_name             = \n| res_capacity_total   = {{convert|258|e6m3|acre feet|abbr=on}}\n| res_capacity_active  =\n| res_capacity_inactive=\n| res_catchment        = \n| res_surface          = {{convert|9.75|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| res_elevation        =\n| res_max_depth        = \n| res_max_length       =\n| res_max_width        =\n| res_tidal_range      = \n| plant_operator       = Sangtudinskaya GES-1\n| plant_commission     = \n| plant_decommission   = \n| plant_type           = [[Run-of-river]] \n| plant_turbines       = 4 x 167.5&nbsp;MW [[Francis turbine]] by [[Power Machines]]\n| plant_capacity       = 670&nbsp;MW\n| plant_annual_gen     = 2,700&nbsp;GWh\n| website              = {{url|http://www.sangtuda.com/}}\n| extra                = \n}}\n'''Sangtuda 1 Hydroelectric Power Plant''' is a [[hydroelectric]] [[power plant]], located on the [[Vakhsh River]] in [[Tajikistan]]. Construction commenced during the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] period in the 1980s, but halted in the beginning of the 1990s due to lack of financing when the station was about 20% complete. An agreement with [[Russia]] allowed to restart the construction, with four units entering service in 2008\u20132009. The plant was officially commissioned on 31 July 2009. Once working at full capacity, the plant will provide around 12% of Tajikistan's electricity output.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Sangtuda 1 commissioning ceremony.jpg|thumb|left|The Russian and Tajik presidents [[Dmitry Medvedev]] and [[Emomalii Rahmon]] simultaneously pushing the symbolic start buttons during the commissioning ceremony of the plant.]]\nPlans to build the power plant were made during the 1970s, with the actual construction commencing in 1989.<ref name=ferghana>\n{{Cite news\n |title       = Who will end up owing Sangtuda\n |author      = Dmitry Glumskov, Natalia Grib\n |work        = [[Kommersant]]\n |publisher   = Ferghana.Ru\n |url         = http://enews.ferghana.ru/article.php?id=600\n |date        = 14 September 2004\n |accessdate  = 8 August 2009\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20061013000717/http://enews.ferghana.ru/article.php?id=600\n |archivedate = 13 October 2006\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}\n</ref>  [[Dissolution of the Soviet Union]], the resulting halt of financing, as well as the [[Civil War in Tajikistan]] interrupted the construction for over a decade. In 1996, the government set up a company for the construction of the power plant and issued public shares. However, the company did not start operating and was liquidated when a deal with Russia was signed.<ref name=asiatimes060110/>\n\nIn October 2004, an intergovernmental agreement was signed by Russia and Tajikistan to complete the project.<ref name=vz>\n{{Cite news\n | title = \u041c\u0435\u0434\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0432 \u0438 \u0420\u0430\u0445\u043c\u043e\u043d \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u044b\u043b\u0438 \u0421\u0430\u043d\u0433\u0442\u0443\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0443\u044e \u0413\u042d\u0421-1 (''Medvedev and Rahmon opened Sangtuda 1'')\n | publisher = Vzglyad\n | url = http://www.vz.ru/news/2009/7/31/313127.html\n | date = 31 July 2009\n | accessdate = 4 August 2009\n | language = Russian}}\n</ref>  In January 2005, Russia, Tajikistan and [[Iran]] signed a protocol according to which Russia would participate in construction of Sangtuda 1 and Iran in construction of Sangtuda 2 power plants.<ref name=vz/>  On 16 February 2005, a joint Russian-Tajik company Sangtudinskaya GES-1 was established.<ref name=asiaplus260610>\n{{Cite news\n | title = Work on cementation of run-of-river part of Sangtuda-1 dam completed\n | first = Payrav | last = Chorshanbiyev\n | publisher = ASIA-Plus\n | url = http://www.asiaplus.tj/en/news/31/66805.html\n | date = 26 June 2010\n | accessdate = 13 November 2010}}\n</ref>  Construction resumed in April 2005.<ref name=vz/><ref name=rian160206>\n{{Cite news\n | title = Tajikistan, Iran, Afghanistan ministers to discuss energy projects\n | agency = [[RIA Novosti]]\n | url = http://en.rian.ru/russia/20060216/43579026.html\n | date = 16 February 2006\n | accessdate = 8 August 2009}}\n</ref>\n\nThe first unit entered service ahead of schedule on 20 January 2008 during the unusually harsh winter, with temperatures dipping below {{convert|-20|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|0}}, which put the Tajik energy system on the brink of collapse.<ref name=market/><ref name=rao310709>\n{{cite press release\n |title       = \u041f\u043e\u0434\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0430\u043d \u0430\u043a\u0442 \u043e \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0435\u043c\u043a\u0435 \u0432 \u044d\u043a\u0441\u043f\u043b\u0443\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044e \u0421\u0430\u043d\u0433\u0442\u0443\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0413\u042d\u0421-1 (''Commissioning act of Sangtuda HPP-1 is signed'')\n |publisher   = [[Inter RAO UES]]\n |url         = http://www.interrao.ru/news/company/266/\n |date        = 31 July 2009\n |accessdate  = 4 August 2009\n |language    = Russian\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090830204846/http://www.interrao.ru/news/company/266/\n |archivedate = 30 August 2009\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}\n</ref>  The second and third units entered service on 1 July 2008, and 15 November 2008, respectively. The fourth and final unit was brought online on 15 May 2009.<ref name=market/>  On 31 July 2009, the plant was officially commissioned, with the presidents of Russia and Tajikistan [[Dmitry Medvedev]] and [[Emomalii Rahmon]] participating in the event.<ref name=itar-tass310709>\n{{Cite news\n |title      = RF, Tajik presidents launch Sangtuda HPP-1\n |publisher  = [[ITAR TASS]]\n |url        = http://www.itar-tass.com/eng/level2.html?NewsID=14195440&PageNum=0\n |date       = 31 July 2009\n |accessdate = 31 July 2009\n}}{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe Sangtuda 1 Hydroelectric Power Plant is located on the Vakhsh River in [[Khatlon]] region, {{convert|160|km|mi}} south of [[Dushanbe]].<ref name=rfe310709>\n{{Cite news\n  | title = Russian, Tajik Presidents Unveil Joint-Venture Power Plant\n  | publisher = [[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]]\n  | url = http://www.rferl.org/content/Russian_Tajik_Presidents_Unveil_Joint_Venture_Power_Plant/1789915.html\n  | date = 31 July 2009\n  | accessdate = 8 August 2009}}\n</ref>  It consist of four units with total capacity of 670&nbsp;MW and producing 2.7&nbsp;TWh electricity per year.<ref name=rao310709/><ref name=reuters151206>\n{{Cite news\n  | title = Tajikistan dams river to fight power shortages\n  | agency = [[Reuters]]\n  | url = http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUKL1579887420061215?sp=true\n  | first = Roman | last = Kozhevnikov\n  | date = 15 December 2006\n  | accessdate = 8 August 2009}}\n</ref>  The construction cost US$720&nbsp;million.<ref name=reuters310709/>  Russian government and companies has 75% of shares and Tajikistan has 25% plus one share.<ref name=turkish010809>\n{{Cite news\n  | title = Dmitry Medvedev's Visit To Tajikistan Not Solves Existing Problems\n  | publisher = [[Turkish Weekly]]\n  | url = http://www.turkishweekly.net/news/85787/-dmitry-medvedev-s-visit-to-tajikistan-not-solves-existing-problems-.html\n  | first = Vitaly | last = Volkov\n  | date = 15 December 2006\n  | accessdate = 8 August 2009}}\n</ref>  The power plant is operated by Sangtudinskaya GES-1, a company controlled by [[Inter RAO UES]].<ref name=market/>  Director of the company is Vladimir Belov.\n\nAs of 2010, all electricity is sold to [[Barqi Tojik]], a national electricity company of Tajikistan.<ref name=asiaplus091010>\n{{Cite news\n | title = Barqi Tojik now owes US$30.8 mln to Sangtudinskaya GES-1\n | first = Zarina | last = Ergasheva\n | publisher = ASIA-Plus\n | url = http://www.asiaplus.tj/en/news/31/70070.html\n | date = 9 October 2010\n | accessdate = 13 November 2010}}\n</ref>  There are plans to construct a [[high-voltage]] [[power transmission line]] to [[Kyrgyzstan]], Iran, [[Afghanistan]], and [[Pakistan]] for the electricity export.<ref name=rian160206/><ref name=rfe210206>\n{{Cite news\n  | title = Tajikistan, Iran, Afghanistan Sign Deal On Electric Power Line\n  | publisher = [[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]]\n  | url = http://www.rferl.org/content/article/1065995.html\n  | date = 21 February 2006\n  | accessdate = 8 August 2009}}\n</ref>  Sangtuda\u2014[[Puli Khumri]] 220&nbsp;kV transmission line to Afghanistan was scheduled to be completed in 2010.<ref name=asiaplus020810>\n{{Cite news\n | title = Construction of power grid from Sangtuda-1 HPP to Afghan border to be completed in September\n | first = Payrav | last = Chorshanbiyev\n | publisher = ASIA-Plus\n | url = http://asiaplus.tj/en/news/31/67953.html\n | date = 2 August 2010\n | accessdate = 13 November 2010}}\n</ref>\n\n==Significance==\nLaunching of the plant is a significant milestone in achieving energy independence for Tajikistan, as the country had experienced severe energy shortages ever since it acquired independence. Tajikistan has experienced a severe shortage of electricity during the winter months for the past fifteen years. In the summer time, Tajikistan exports its electricity surplus to surrounding countries, and in the winter time Tajikistan experiences rolling blackouts.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://centralasiaonline.com/en_GB/articles/caii/features/2009/05/21/feature-05|title=Last system at Tajikistan\u2019s Sangtuda power plant started up|publisher=Central Asia Online |accessdate=18 July 2012}}</ref> The plant provides around 12% of Tajikistan's electricity output.<ref name=reuters310709>\n{{Cite news\n  | title = Russia boosts C. Asia ties, opens plant in Tajikistan\n  | publisher = [[Reuters]]\n  | url = http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUKLV616217?sp=true\n  | first1 = Roman | last1 = Kozhevnikov\n  | first2 = Anastasia | last2 = Onegina\n  | date = 31 July 2009\n  | accessdate = 4 August 2009}}\n</ref>\n\nThe plant is the largest project within the [[Commonwealth of Independent States]] with participation of the Russian companies, including [[Power Machines]], Chekhov Gidrostal Plant, ChirkeyGESstroy, Zarubezhvodstroy, Zagranenergostroymontazh, and Trust Gidromontazh.<ref name=market>\n{{Cite news\n |title       = In Tajikistan, started Sangtuda HPP-1\n |publisher   = Market Analysis\n |url         = http://dotnetpalm.net/Company-News/in-tajikistan-started-sangtuda-hpp-1/\n |date        = 31 July 2009\n |accessdate  = 8 August 2009\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090811031343/http://dotnetpalm.net/Company-News/in-tajikistan-started-sangtuda-hpp-1/\n |archivedate = 11 August 2009\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}\n</ref><ref name=reuters310709/>  Both the Tajik and the Russian presidents have noted that the project has contributed significantly to strengthening the [[Russia\u2013Tajikistan relations|relations between the two countries]].<ref name=reuters310709/>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn 1996, public shares of the company for the construction of the power plant were issued. After dissolving this company it remained unclear how the owners of shares are to be compensated.<ref name=asiatimes060110/>  Some of Tajikistan's neighbours, especially [[Uzbekistan]], are concerned that construction of large hydroelectric plants within the [[headwater]]s of the region's rivers will result in shortages of water downstream.<ref name=asiatimes060110>\n{{Cite news\n | title = Tajiks feel pinch in funding dam\n | first = Jahongir | last = Boboev\n | newspaper = [[Asia Times Online]]\n | url = http://www.atimes.com/atimes/Central_Asia/LA06Ag01.html\n | date = 6 January 2010\n | accessdate = 13 November 2010}}\n</ref>\n\nUzbekistan, Kazakhstan and Turkmenistan are concerned that the filling of the power plant's reservoir and the actual operation of the power plant will harm the water needed for their crop production.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://oilprice.com/Latest-Energy-News/World-News/Tajikistan-To-Export-Electricity-To-Afghanistan.html|title=Tajikistan to Export Electricity to Afghanistan|publisher=OilPrice.com |accessdate=18 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nWithdrawal of Uzbekistan from the Central Asian [[unified power system]] also cut Tajikistan off from the system and blocked electricity export via Uzbek to southern Kazakhstan. Because of this, the plant can't utilize its full capacity. Rail traffic blockade by Uzbekistan had delayed construction of transmission lines from the plant to Afghanistan and Kyrgyzstan.<ref name=asiaplus300710>\n{{Cite news\n | title = Energy blockade reportedly costs Sangtudinskaya GES-1 at US$20 mln\n | first = Payrav | last = Chorshanbiyev\n | publisher = ASIA-Plus\n | url = http://asiaplus.tj/en/news/31/67921.html\n | date = 30 July 2010\n | accessdate = 13 November 2010}}\n</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{stack|{{Portal|Tajikistan|Water|Renewable energy}}}}\n{{Vakhsh River dams}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hydroelectric power stations in Tajikistan]]\n[[Category:Hydroelectric power stations built in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Russia\u2013Tajikistan relations]]\n[[Category:Inter RAO]]\n[[Category:Dams on the Vakhsh River]]\n[[Category:Khatlon Region]]\n[[Category:Embankment dams]]\n[[Category:Dams completed in 2009]]\n[[Category:Energy infrastructure completed in 2009]]\n[[Category:2009 establishments in Tajikistan]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox dam\n| name                 = Sangtuda 1 Hydroelectric Power Plant\n| name_official        = Sangtudinskaya GES-1\n| image                = Sangtuda 1.jpg\n| image_size           = \n| image_caption        = Sangtuda 1 Hydroelectric Power Plant\n| image_alt            = \n| location_map         = Tajikistan\n| location_map_size    = \n| location_map_caption = Location of the Sangtuda 1 Hydroelectric Power Plant within Tajikistan\n| coordinates          = {{coord|38|02|42|N|69|03|30|E|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n| country              = [[Tajikistan]]\n| location             = [[Danghara District]], [[Khatlon Province]]\n| status               = O\n| construction_began   = 1989\n| opening              = 2009\n| demolished           = \n| cost                 = US$720&nbsp;million\n| owner                = [[Government of Russia]] (66.39%)<br>[[Government of Tajikistan]] (16.45%)<br>[[FGC UES]] (14.92%)<br>[[Inter RAO UES]] (2.24%)\n| dam_type             = \n| dam_height           = {{convert|75|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| dam_height_thalweg   =\n| dam_height_foundation=\n| dam_length           = {{convert|517|m|ft|0|abbr=on}}\n| dam_width_crest      = \n| dam_width_base       = \n| dam_volume           = \n| dam_elevation_crest  =\n| dam_crosses          = [[Vakhsh River]]\n| spillway_count       = \n| spillway_type        = \n| spillway_capacity    = \n| res_name             = \n| res_capacity_total   = {{convert|258|e6m3|acre feet|abbr=on}}\n| res_capacity_active  =\n| res_capacity_inactive=\n| res_catchment        = \n| res_surface          = {{convert|9.75|km2|sqmi|abbr=on}}\n| res_elevation        =\n| res_max_depth        = \n| res_max_length       =\n| res_max_width        =\n| res_tidal_range      = \n| plant_operator       = Sangtudinskaya GES-1\n| plant_commission     = \n| plant_decommission   = \n| plant_type           = [[Run-of-river]] \n| plant_turbines       = 4 x 167.5&nbsp;MW [[Francis turbine]] by [[Power Machines]]\n| plant_capacity       = 670&nbsp;MW\n| plant_annual_gen     = 2,700&nbsp;GWh\n| website              = {{url|http://www.sangtuda.com/}}\n| extra                = \n}}\n'''Sangtuda 1 Hydroelectric Power Plant''' is a [[hydroelectric]] [[power plant]], located on the [[Vakhsh River]] in [[Tajikistan]]. Construction commenced during the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] period in the 1980s, but halted in the beginning of the 1990s due to lack of financing when the station was about 20% complete. An agreement with [[Russia]] allowed to restart the construction, with four units entering service in 2008\u20132009. The plant was officially commissioned on 31 July 2009. Once working at full capacity, the plant will provide around 12% of Tajikistan's electricity output.\n\n==History==\n[[File:Sangtuda 1 commissioning ceremony.jpg|thumb|left|The Russian and Tajik presidents [[Dmitry Medvedev]] and [[Emomalii Rahmon]] simultaneously pushing the symbolic start buttons during the commissioning ceremony of the plant.]]\nPlans to build the power plant were made during the 1970s, with the actual construction commencing in 1989.<ref name=ferghana>\n{{Cite news\n |title       = Who will end up owing Sangtuda\n |author      = Dmitry Glumskov, Natalia Grib\n |work        = [[Kommersant]]\n |publisher   = Ferghana.Ru\n |url         = http://enews.ferghana.ru/article.php?id=600\n |date        = 14 September 2004\n |accessdate  = 8 August 2009\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20061013000717/http://enews.ferghana.ru/article.php?id=600\n |archivedate = 13 October 2006\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}\n</ref>  [[Dissolution of the Soviet Union]], the resulting halt of financing, as well as the [[Civil War in Tajikistan]] interrupted the construction for over a decade. In 1996, the government set up a company for the construction of the power plant and issued public shares. However, the company did not start operating and was liquidated when a deal with Russia was signed.<ref name=asiatimes060110/>\n\nIn October 2004, an intergovernmental agreement was signed by Russia and Tajikistan to complete the project.<ref name=vz>\n{{Cite news\n | title = \u041c\u0435\u0434\u0432\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0432 \u0438 \u0420\u0430\u0445\u043c\u043e\u043d \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u044b\u043b\u0438 \u0421\u0430\u043d\u0433\u0442\u0443\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0443\u044e \u0413\u042d\u0421-1 (''Medvedev and Rahmon opened Sangtuda 1'')\n | publisher = Vzglyad\n | url = http://www.vz.ru/news/2009/7/31/313127.html\n | date = 31 July 2009\n | accessdate = 4 August 2009\n | language = Russian}}\n</ref>  In January 2005, Russia, Tajikistan and [[Iran]] signed a protocol according to which Russia would participate in construction of Sangtuda 1 and Iran in construction of Sangtuda 2 power plants.<ref name=vz/>  On 16 February 2005, a joint Russian-Tajik company Sangtudinskaya GES-1 was established.<ref name=asiaplus260610>\n{{Cite news\n | title = Work on cementation of run-of-river part of Sangtuda-1 dam completed\n | first = Payrav | last = Chorshanbiyev\n | publisher = ASIA-Plus\n | url = http://www.asiaplus.tj/en/news/31/66805.html\n | date = 26 June 2010\n | accessdate = 13 November 2010}}\n</ref>  Construction resumed in April 2005.<ref name=vz/><ref name=rian160206>\n{{Cite news\n | title = Tajikistan, Iran, Afghanistan ministers to discuss energy projects\n | agency = [[RIA Novosti]]\n | url = http://en.rian.ru/russia/20060216/43579026.html\n | date = 16 February 2006\n | accessdate = 8 August 2009}}\n</ref>\n\nThe first unit entered service ahead of schedule on 20 January 2008 during the unusually harsh winter, with temperatures dipping below {{convert|-20|\u00b0C|\u00b0F|0}}, which put the Tajik energy system on the brink of collapse.<ref name=market/><ref name=rao310709>\n{{cite press release\n |title       = \u041f\u043e\u0434\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0430\u043d \u0430\u043a\u0442 \u043e \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0435\u043c\u043a\u0435 \u0432 \u044d\u043a\u0441\u043f\u043b\u0443\u0430\u0442\u0430\u0446\u0438\u044e \u0421\u0430\u043d\u0433\u0442\u0443\u0434\u0438\u043d\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u0413\u042d\u0421-1 (''Commissioning act of Sangtuda HPP-1 is signed'')\n |publisher   = [[Inter RAO UES]]\n |url         = http://www.interrao.ru/news/company/266/\n |date        = 31 July 2009\n |accessdate  = 4 August 2009\n |language    = Russian\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090830204846/http://www.interrao.ru/news/company/266/\n |archivedate = 30 August 2009\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}\n</ref>  The second and third units entered service on 1 July 2008, and 15 November 2008, respectively. The fourth and final unit was brought online on 15 May 2009.<ref name=market/>  On 31 July 2009, the plant was officially commissioned, with the presidents of Russia and Tajikistan [[Dmitry Medvedev]] and [[Emomalii Rahmon]] participating in the event.<ref name=itar-tass310709>\n{{Cite news\n |title      = RF, Tajik presidents launch Sangtuda HPP-1\n |publisher  = [[ITAR TASS]]\n |url        = http://www.itar-tass.com/eng/level2.html?NewsID=14195440&PageNum=0\n |date       = 31 July 2009\n |accessdate = 31 July 2009\n}}{{dead link|date=May 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n</ref>\n\n==Description==\nThe Sangtuda 1 Hydroelectric Power Plant is located on the Vakhsh River in [[Khatlon]] region, {{convert|160|km|mi}} south of [[Dushanbe]].<ref name=rfe310709>\n{{Cite news\n  | title = Russian, Tajik Presidents Unveil Joint-Venture Power Plant\n  | publisher = [[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]]\n  | url = http://www.rferl.org/content/Russian_Tajik_Presidents_Unveil_Joint_Venture_Power_Plant/1789915.html\n  | date = 31 July 2009\n  | accessdate = 8 August 2009}}\n</ref>  It consist of four units with total capacity of 670&nbsp;MW and producing 2.7&nbsp;TWh electricity per year.<ref name=rao310709/><ref name=reuters151206>\n{{Cite news\n  | title = Tajikistan dams river to fight power shortages\n  | agency = [[Reuters]]\n  | url = http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUKL1579887420061215?sp=true\n  | first = Roman | last = Kozhevnikov\n  | date = 15 December 2006\n  | accessdate = 8 August 2009}}\n</ref>  The construction cost US$720&nbsp;million.<ref name=reuters310709/>  Russian government and companies has 75% of shares and Tajikistan has 25% plus one share.<ref name=turkish010809>\n{{Cite news\n  | title = Dmitry Medvedev's Visit To Tajikistan Not Solves Existing Problems\n  | publisher = [[Turkish Weekly]]\n  | url = http://www.turkishweekly.net/news/85787/-dmitry-medvedev-s-visit-to-tajikistan-not-solves-existing-problems-.html\n  | first = Vitaly | last = Volkov\n  | date = 15 December 2006\n  | accessdate = 8 August 2009}}\n</ref>  The power plant is operated by Sangtudinskaya GES-1, a company controlled by [[Inter RAO UES]].<ref name=market/>  Director of the company is Vladimir Belov.\n\nAs of 2010, all electricity is sold to [[Barqi Tojik]], a national electricity company of Tajikistan.<ref name=asiaplus091010>\n{{Cite news\n | title = Barqi Tojik now owes US$30.8 mln to Sangtudinskaya GES-1\n | first = Zarina | last = Ergasheva\n | publisher = ASIA-Plus\n | url = http://www.asiaplus.tj/en/news/31/70070.html\n | date = 9 October 2010\n | accessdate = 13 November 2010}}\n</ref>  There are plans to construct a [[high-voltage]] [[power transmission line]] to [[Kyrgyzstan]], Iran, [[Afghanistan]], and [[Pakistan]] for the electricity export.<ref name=rian160206/><ref name=rfe210206>\n{{Cite news\n  | title = Tajikistan, Iran, Afghanistan Sign Deal On Electric Power Line\n  | publisher = [[Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty]]\n  | url = http://www.rferl.org/content/article/1065995.html\n  | date = 21 February 2006\n  | accessdate = 8 August 2009}}\n</ref>  Sangtuda\u2014[[Puli Khumri]] 220&nbsp;kV transmission line to Afghanistan was scheduled to be completed in 2010.<ref name=asiaplus020810>\n{{Cite news\n | title = Construction of power grid from Sangtuda-1 HPP to Afghan border to be completed in September\n | first = Payrav | last = Chorshanbiyev\n | publisher = ASIA-Plus\n | url = http://asiaplus.tj/en/news/31/67953.html\n | date = 2 August 2010\n | accessdate = 13 November 2010}}\n</ref>\n\n==Significance==\nLaunching of the plant is a significant milestone in achieving energy independence for Tajikistan, as the country had experienced severe energy shortages ever since it acquired independence. Tajikistan has experienced a severe shortage of electricity during the winter months for the past fifteen years. In the summer time, Tajikistan exports its electricity surplus to surrounding countries, and in the winter time Tajikistan experiences rolling blackouts.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://centralasiaonline.com/en_GB/articles/caii/features/2009/05/21/feature-05|title=Last system at Tajikistan\u2019s Sangtuda power plant started up|publisher=Central Asia Online |accessdate=18 July 2012}}</ref> The plant provides around 12% of Tajikistan's electricity output.<ref name=reuters310709>\n{{Cite news\n  | title = Russia boosts C. Asia ties, opens plant in Tajikistan\n  | publisher = [[Reuters]]\n  | url = http://uk.reuters.com/article/idUKLV616217?sp=true\n  | first1 = Roman | last1 = Kozhevnikov\n  | first2 = Anastasia | last2 = Onegina\n  | date = 31 July 2009\n  | accessdate = 4 August 2009}}\n</ref>\n\nThe plant is the largest project within the [[Commonwealth of Independent States]] with participation of the Russian companies, including [[Power Machines]], Chekhov Gidrostal Plant, ChirkeyGESstroy, Zarubezhvodstroy, Zagranenergostroymontazh, and Trust Gidromontazh.<ref name=market>\n{{Cite news\n |title       = In Tajikistan, started Sangtuda HPP-1\n |publisher   = Market Analysis\n |url         = http://dotnetpalm.net/Company-News/in-tajikistan-started-sangtuda-hpp-1/\n |date        = 31 July 2009\n |accessdate  = 8 August 2009\n |url-status     = dead\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20090811031343/http://dotnetpalm.net/Company-News/in-tajikistan-started-sangtuda-hpp-1/\n |archivedate = 11 August 2009\n |df          = dmy-all\n}}\n</ref><ref name=reuters310709/>  Both the Tajik and the Russian presidents have noted that the project has contributed significantly to strengthening the [[Russia\u2013Tajikistan relations|relations between the two countries]].<ref name=reuters310709/>\n\n==Controversies==\nIn 1996, public shares of the company for the construction of the power plant were issued. After dissolving this company it remained unclear how the owners of shares are to be compensated.<ref name=asiatimes060110/>  Some of Tajikistan's neighbours, especially [[Uzbekistan]], are concerned that construction of large hydroelectric plants within the [[headwater]]s of the region's rivers will result in shortages of water downstream.<ref name=asiatimes060110>\n{{Cite news\n | title = Tajiks feel pinch in funding dam\n | first = Jahongir | last = Boboev\n | newspaper = [[Asia Times Online]]\n | url = http://www.atimes.com/atimes/Central_Asia/LA06Ag01.html\n | date = 6 January 2010\n | accessdate = 13 November 2010}}\n</ref>\n\nUzbekistan, Kazakhstan and Turkmenistan are concerned that the filling of the power plant's reservoir and the actual operation of the power plant will harm the water needed for their crop production.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://oilprice.com/Latest-Energy-News/World-News/Tajikistan-To-Export-Electricity-To-Afghanistan.html|title=Tajikistan to Export Electricity to Afghanistan|publisher=OilPrice.com |accessdate=18 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nWithdrawal of Uzbekistan from the Central Asian [[unified power system]] also cut Tajikistan off from the system and blocked electricity export via Uzbek to southern Kazakhstan. Because of this, the plant can't utilize its full capacity. Rail traffic blockade by Uzbekistan had delayed construction of transmission lines from the plant to Afghanistan and Kyrgyzstan.<ref name=asiaplus300710>\n{{Cite news\n | title = Energy blockade reportedly costs Sangtudinskaya GES-1 at US$20 mln\n | first = Payrav | last = Chorshanbiyev\n | publisher = ASIA-Plus\n | url = http://asiaplus.tj/en/news/31/67921.html\n | date = 30 July 2010\n | accessdate = 13 November 2010}}\n</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2010}}\n\n{{stack|{{Portal|Tajikistan|Water|Renewable energy}}}}\n{{Vakhsh River dams}}\n\n[[Category:Hydroelectric power stations in Tajikistan]]\n[[Category:Hydroelectric power stations built in the Soviet Union]]\n[[Category:Russia\u2013Tajikistan relations]]\n[[Category:Inter RAO]]\n[[Category:Dams on the Vakhsh River]]\n[[Category:Khatlon Region]]\n[[Category:Embankment dams]]\n[[Category:Dams completed in 2009]]\n[[Category:Energy infrastructure completed in 2009]]\n[[Category:2009 establishments in Tajikistan]]\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:Update date format tag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sangtuda_1_Hydroelectric_Power_Plant"}
